Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon
Long before Turkey intended to join the European Union, the European powers were burning with the desire to penetrate deeply into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps just 20 steps from the European border, stands one of the greatest relics of the failed imperial endeavor.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that's what the guidebooks say.
The building encompasses the ends of the platforms, with one tower at each of the front corners, and looks like a German town hall in the countryside.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building's a little bumpy.
However, looking at the interior of the vaulted ticket office, it is obvious what a large-scale enterprise this had been the most western gate.
The station was opened by the German consortium Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future" of the conquests, wanted to realize its ambitions of conquering the Middle East with the help of this railway from Damascus through Baghdad to present-day Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab partisans.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The Hyderpasha station didn't get any better.
In 1917, a ammunition train exploded and destroyed the beautifully crafted roof of the building.
According to Turkish sources, there was a sabotage operation.
Since then, it has slowly collapsed, and history has gone far beyond it.
At the same time, today, as a gateway to the railways to Anatolia and the entire eastern region, it serves - at least in a symbolic sense - as Turkey's expanding diplomatic horizon.
The Justice and Development Party in government -- the AKP -- has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
Relative isolation from the surrounding regions, caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
The new policy is characterized by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government maintains good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to assess the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I boarded the night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, to visit one of the AKP’s leading foreign policy experts, the Turkish parliamentarian Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning, after about ten and a half hours of turmoil, which also gave me the rhythm of the famous documentary about the old world, "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital. The new city is destined for the symbol of the new secular state, which turns its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which is known to have Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This has raised some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern building made of stone and steel, specially designed for this purpose - located in a developing suburban area, between half-finished shopping malls and coffee houses. In the latter, middle-managers in suits - both men and women - meet to start a business early in the morning.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have belonged to a right-middle-minded politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
“The party’s foreign policy goal is to help Turkey re-integrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has upset the order,” he said.
Turkey is isolated from its hinterland.
Today he had to turn east and west at the same time.
He couldn't choose between the two.
It had to open in both directions.
"Is it possible that sooner or later you will be forced to vote?" he asked.
"Turkey never wanted to face a choice."
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here almost mechanically repeated: Turkey’s relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the countries surrounding the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey itself.
It is as if they were trying to convey the message that together with Turkey, in a figurative sense, the whole of Europe can reach Asia and the Middle East on those east-bound railway lines.
When I was again at the Hydarpasha station, after another night, mostly awake, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who had witnessed the construction of this ornamental structure 100 years ago.
How they would be surprised to learn that the ambitions of Europe in the Middle East are now largely in the hands of Turkey.
And as I waited at the harbor for the ferry to take me back across the Bosphorus, I remembered that at the time Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe."
At the time, at least, there was no question as to which continent would claim this exciting country.
Memorable Life Paths: Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: Since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (necrologist, Sept. 11) has been Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir as Guildford Music Director.
The following year, on the basis of his musical plans for the district, he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus.
In principle, only those under the age of 21 should have been part of the choir, but when Proteus sang its finale in 1979 - many of us were in our late 20s - we simply refused to leave the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the name of the mythological shape-shifter) was consistent with the choir's determination and ability to cope with any sheet music that was put in front of it - whether it was a madrigal or a piece of Messiaen; without an accompaniment, or with an orchestral accompaniment.
The musical versatility of such a young choir was often astonishing and always exciting, and we owe it to the man whose inspiration our enthusiasm for music has remained unchanged over the years.
How often did Tod tell us, "Let the music play itself."
He always said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all in the sheet music.
So sing it!"
His conducting technique was always perfectly understandable and accurate, but never dictatorial or exaggerated.
Whatever the level of music he was, he always raised it.
John Frayn Turner wrote:
If there ever was a choir leader who should have been knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I got to know him well during the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
In the past forty or so years, I have written reviews of more than 100 concerts, but I have never been disappointed by one, and I have often been thrilled by them.
Tod Handley had greatness and modesty together, which is very rare.
He hated the conductors who, in his words, simply "walked around the world with one or two well-known battle horses."
Many of us will miss him.
