The collision avoiding "bee car"
For the development of accident-prevention technologies, Nissan has this time drawn inspiration from nature, specifically from the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company has designed a robot to avoid accidents by imitating the bee’s flight.
The Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C could be the first step in the development of collision prevention technologies.
The engineers at Nissan Motor Co.’s Advanced Technology Center, in cooperation with the renowned University of Tokyo’s Advanced Science and Technology Research Center, built this small robot in Japan.
Kazuhhiro Doi, Chief Technology Officer for Public Relations and Research and Development, defines the BR23C as a further extension of Nissan’s four-level safety cover.
The robot enhances the collision avoidance capability of the company’s products.
During flight, each bee creates its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety cover.
More important, however, is the complex eye of the uterus, with which it can see at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, so that the uterus can fly uninterrupted in its own personal space.
To replicate the function of the composite eye, engineers designed a so-called laser range finder.
With a field of vision of 180 degrees ahead of the BR23C, the instrument identifies obstacles, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which is instantly transformed into a collision avoidance operation.
"As soon as the obstacle is detected, the small robot immediately changes direction by simulating the movements of the uterus by moving the wheels at a smaller or larger angle to avoid collision.
What distinguishes the system from the instruments currently available is that in this case the avoidance maneuver is fully automatic.
If this were not the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the bypassing maneuver cannot be directed upwards or downwards or diagonally, but can only move in two dimensions and exclusively in the direction of the turning of the wheels, i.e. not in an infinite direction and way, as in the case of bees.
That’s why Nissan used a rotational function in the robot, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to avoid collisions.
“This device only needs to process and respond to data every few seconds.
There is no need for data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but it’s really not gigabytes, and we’re not even talking about megabytes of memory.
This is the first step in the development of an instant collision prevention technology, which Nissan estimates will be available for mass-produced cars within 10 years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system could be an additional application in order to get the driver to the final destination by avoiding obstacles on the road.
