Fox in the henhouse
In the U.S., life and health insurance companies often refuse to enter into an insurance contract with an applicant based on people’s drug purchase data.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
"There is a data protection programme that always requires the consent of the person concerned to use the prescribing data.
This must be in independent hands, or else we will leave the henhouse to the fox," said Richard Dick, the developer of the drug tracking program.
Insurance companies make the premium and the amount of the damages dependent on the health condition of the client, and if they consider the risk to be too high, they do not take out insurance with it.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination, and the contract was concluded only after the result of the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: he can easily obtain from pharmacies the medications he has bought in the last year and a half based on the customer’s ID number, and from this the program itself draws conclusions about the disease he has and his health condition.
For example, if you regularly take high doses of cholesterol-lowering drugs, it suggests that you have virtually uncontrollably high blood fat levels, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
Several versions of the program are in circulation, some of them also specify a risk multiplier, so the insurer has little to do outside the paperwork, although small difficulties may arise.
The disadvantages include that some drugs can be used for multiple purposes, for example, some compounds can be used against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, not the former.
Separate companies have been set up to retrieve and process the data, and before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, they ask for the patient’s consent.
They are now obliged to do so by the authorities, although they have not been penalized for their previous omissions.
Recently, some companies are also processing the results of laboratory tests and combining them with data on drug consumption, so they can provide an even more accurate picture of the patient’s health.
More and more companies are gaining access to the data, and it is becoming increasingly difficult to control its use.
There is a separate health data protection law, but its scope only covers health care providers and insurers.
A bill is in front of Congress that gives the authorities control over companies specializing in data provision.
Dick Richard understands that this is not enough: he has therefore further developed his programme, which would make the transfer of data subjects subject to their explicit consent.
Another issue is that the person concerned can hardly refuse the consent, otherwise the insurers will not enter into a contract with him.
So the hens are somewhat dependent on the fox's benevolence.
